<br>
There were many ideas for what we should ask Verant to help us with, far too many for me to include in a document of that nature.<br>
<br>
As part of writing it, I'll admit that I took it upon myself to look at what Tweil collected on the Grove.org site, and what was recurring in the various threads discussing issues, and limited the requests to A) Those things which seemed to be the most sought after changes; and, B) Those things which seemed most likely to be considered by Verant.<br>
<br>
For most of the game Druids did fine without a pet.  Our pet is useless, so it has zero impact on our balance in the high end game.  The pet, much like Wake of Karana, is gravy.  Something to have for the sake of having.  Would it be nice for it be useful? Of course.  Is it essential to our development as a class? No.  Would the repurcussions of Verant making it a miniature familiar be so large and loud that Verant wouldn't even consider it? Yes.  <br>
<br>
We all know wizards would throw a fit.  Every other post for months afterwards on Graffe's would be a call to have Druid's nerfed, or have their familiars made better, because &quot;Wizards are supposed to be the Masters of Familiars!&quot;  <br>
<br>
You'd end up with clerics wanting their hammer to be a familiar and shaman wanting their pet to not only fight, but also give them stat increases.  Monks would start suggesting that Boo Boo means a druid can replace a them as pullers, and warriors would suggest we can taunt better than they can now with our pet.  Mages would probably storm Verant HQ and burn it down for making druid pets better in some way than mage pets.<br>
<br>
Verant isn't going to subject themselves to that to make the single most hated class in the game better off. <p><p><center><img src=http://lilyanaeq.homestead.com/files/Signatures/Aidon.jpg>
<BR> <a target="new" href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=24579">Aidon</a>

